# The plan, and where it was wrong

This document was written *before* the analysis and *edited after*, and both
versions are kept. The strikethrough is deliberate. A plan that was never wrong
about anything is a plan that was written afterwards.

Every figure below is generated by `src/analysis.py` into `reports/results.json`
and verified by `src/check_docs.py`. Nothing here is typed by hand — the first
draft of this document was, and every number in it was stale within a day.

---

## The question, as it arrived from Operations

> *"Why is customer retention falling when our fill rate has stayed above 95%?"*

Fill rate is the metric a quick-commerce ops team lives on — reported per shift,
per store, per picker. It is an **operations metric being read as a customer
metric**, and nobody had connected a missing item at 19:04 on a Tuesday to a
customer who quietly stopped ordering in March.

## Why this needs a warehouse and not a query

| Source system | Grain | Clock | Latency |
|---|---|---|---|
| Order service (events) | one row per *event* | UTC | real-time, with retries |
| Order service (items) | one row per *order-item* | — | real-time |
| Warehouse ops | one row per *fulfilment* | UTC | **up to 6h late** |
| App analytics | one row per *session* | UTC | real-time |
| Catalogue | one row per *product version* | — | SCD2 |
| Ops master data | one row per *darkstore version* | — | SCD2 |
| CRM | one row per *customer* | — | daily |
| Experiment platform | one row per *assignment* | UTC | real-time |

Three grains, two latencies, one timezone mismatch, two slowly-changing
dimensions. The business speaks GST; every system logs UTC. This is not a query.
This is a data model.

---

## Hypotheses, stated before looking

**H1 — the grain trap.** Item-level and order-level fill rate will diverge,
because an order is clean only if *every* item is. Expected to matter.

**H2 — the confound.** ~~Heavy users order more, so they are more exposed to
stock-outs, and they retain better for unrelated reasons. The naive comparison
will be biased **toward zero**, hiding real damage.~~

**H3 — tenure moderates.** A stock-out on order #1 is evidence the service does
not work. A stock-out on order #30 is a Tuesday.

**H4 — the experiment will look clean and be broken.** Assignment at session
start, exposure at checkout, treatment UI adds a step.

---

## What the data said

### H1 — confirmed, and it is the finding

| | |
|---|---|
| **Item-level fill rate** | **{item_fill}** — the number on the ops dashboard |
| **Order-level fill rate** | **{order_fill}** — the number the customer experiences |
| Gap | **{gap_pp} percentage points** |

Both numbers are correct. They describe the same {items} items and
{orders} orders. They differ only in grain.

Operations was right: fill rate never dropped below 95% at the item level. They
were reading a true number that could not answer their question.

The mechanism: an order survives only if every item does, so
`P(clean order) ≈ (1 − p)^basket_size`. At a {item_miss} item
miss rate and a {mean_basket}-item mean basket, roughly a third of orders
are broken by construction.

**The inversion is what makes it a decision, not a curiosity:**

| Basket size | Orders | Item fill | Order fill |
|---|---|---|---|
{basket_table}

Read the two right-hand columns against each other. **Item fill rate says large
baskets are served slightly *better*. Order fill rate says they are served
*twice as badly*.** Same data, same period, opposite conclusion — and large
baskets are the Weekly Stock-Up segment, the highest-value customers on the
platform.

The metric the operation optimises actively conceals that its best customers get
its worst experience. (Spearman ρ = {rho_item}
for item fill vs basket, {rho_order} for
order fill — monotonic, opposite directions.)

### H2 — **rejected.** Real in exposure, absent in outcome.

Basket size drives stock-out exposure enormously:

| Basket quintile | Mean items | Stock-out rate | Baseline repeat (clean orders) |
|---|---|---|---|
{gradient_table}

Exposure nearly triples across the range, so the confound *should* bite. But
baseline repeat is flat and non-monotonic across the same range, so basket size
is a **strong exposure confounder and a weak outcome confounder**. Adjusting for
it barely moves the estimate:

```
naive              {naive_pp} pp
basket-stratified  {strat_pp} pp
shift              {shift_pp} pp
```

**Reported as a negative result rather than deleted.** The adjustment was run
because the hypothesis was reasonable; it did not change the answer; that is
information. An analysis that only shows the adjustments that worked is not an
analysis, it is an argument.

This finding also pays off later: it is *why* the experiment's basket-selection
bug does not manufacture a fake win. The project is consistent with itself.

### H3 — confirmed, and this is where the decision lives

| Tenure | Focal orders | Clean repeat | Stock-out repeat | Effect | 95% CI |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
{tenure_table}

The pooled **{naive_pp} pp** is a weighted average of two
populations that need opposite decisions. It is not a number anyone should act on.

A stock-out costs roughly **{ratio}×
more** on a new customer's basket than an established one — and new customers are
{new_share} of focal orders.

**And the missing item's identity matters.** When the stocked-out item was
high-intent — the reason the customer opened the app — the extra damage is
**{hi_pp} pp** [{hi_lo}, {hi_hi}] versus other
stocked-out orders. A flat fill-rate target cannot express this.

### H4 — confirmed, and worse than predicted

See `docs/06_experimentation.md`. Summary: the experiment's SRM is real, but the
trap is not a fake win — it is a fake **harmless**.

---

## What this buys the business

Not "improve fill rate." Everyone already wants that, and it is not free — you
buy fill rate with inventory, which is the one thing a darkstore has no room for.

1. **Stop reporting item fill rate as the headline.** It is the number that makes
   the operation look best and the customer feel worst.
2. **Weight fill-rate investment toward first baskets**, where the damage is
   ~{ratio}× larger, and
   toward high-intent categories.
3. **Normalise stock-out exposure per item, not per customer.** A per-customer
   stock-out rate ranks your best customers as your worst-served, because they
   buy more things.

---

## Limitations, stated here rather than buried

Full list in `docs/07_limitations.md`. The three that matter:

- **The data is synthetic.** Structure is realistic; magnitudes are invented. The
  {item_fill} / {order_fill} gap is a property of the
  generative process, not a measurement of any real operator. What transfers is
  the *method* and the *mechanism*, not the numbers.
- **The causal estimate is observational.** Stock-outs were not randomised, so
  the tenure figures are associations under a stated adjustment set, not
  experimental effects. The experiment layer exists because of this.
- **The 30-day window censors the back of the panel.** Focal orders are
  restricted to those with 30 clear days of follow-up, which drops the final
  month and biases toward earlier-acquired customers.
